{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489574","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489574"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:21:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:21:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"693"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"693","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/693"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.37,0.4,0.03,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"693"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44032"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"693","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/693"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"693"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29013"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"112"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"2116"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5764"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6717"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44623"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44032","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44032"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man undergoes a transrectal ultrasound-guided (TRUS) biopsy of his prostate as part of an assessment of possible prostate carcinoma. A Gleason score will be determined.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following most accurately determines the components of this score?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prostate-specific antigen (PSA) + MRI features","Cytological features","Architectural features","Sonographic findings during TRUS","Digital rectal examination (DRE) findings and clinical presentation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe Gleason score is a pathological measure of the degree of mutation in prostate cancer. The Gleason score consists of a primary + secondary grade. Grading is based on \u003Cstrong\u003Earchitectural features\u003C/strong\u003E of the tissue biopsy ranging from a score of 1 (well differentiated) to 5 (poorly differentiated). The primary grade indicates the most prevalent architectural pattern, and the secondary grade indicates the next most prevalent architectural pattern (eg. 4+3).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECytological features\u003C/strong\u003E are by definition the examination of a single cell and is mainly from fluid specimens. While cytology can be used to diagnose and screen for cancer (i.e. Pap smears), trans-perineal biopsy of the prostate does not look at a single cell but rather the collection and pattern of malignant cellular change.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI, \u003C/strong\u003Ewhile an integral part of assessment, is not considered in the Gleason score. Nor are \u003Cstrong\u003EPSA, sonographic findings during TRUS, digital rectal examination (DRE) findings and clinical presentation \u003C/strong\u003Econsidered as part of the score.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The Gleason score is a score looking at prostatic tissue biopsy and the ubiquity of cellular malignant changes.","The Gleason score consists of a primary + secondary grade.","Grading is based on the architecture of the tissue biopsy ranging from a score of 1 (well differentiated) to 5 (poorly differentiated).","The primary grade indicates the most prevalent architectural pattern, and the secondary grade indicates the next most prevalent architectural pattern (e.g. 4+3)"],"references":["Humphrey P. Gleason grading and prognostic factors in carcinoma of the prostate. Mod Pathol. 2004; 17;292-306. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/14976540/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29013"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"693"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29013","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29013"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-04-05T16:35:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-04-05T16:35:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"693"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44032"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"112","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/112"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Prostate cancer","synonyms":["Prostate tumour","Prostate malignancy",